Halve the @bell pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Chop into 1cm chunks. Trim the @carrot{1}, then coarsely grate (no need to peel). Peel and grate the @garlic{3%cloves} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Heat a large #frying pan{} on high heat (no oil).

Once the pan is hot, add the pepper and cook until charred, ~{5-6%minutes}. Adjust the heat if necessary. Stir only twice during this time - you want the pepper to pick up some nice colour.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of oil in a medium #saucepan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add half the garlic and cook for ~{1%minute}. Stir in the @bulgur wheat{110%g} and cook until coated, ~{1%minute}.

Add the @water{240%ml} for the bulgur and half the @chicken stock paste{20%g} and bring to the boil.

Simmer for ~{1%minute}. Pop a #lid{} on the pan and remove from the heat. Leave to the side for ~{12-15%minutes} or until ready to serve.

To the pan with the charred pepper, add the @British pork mince{240%g} and carrot. Fry until the meat has browned and carrot has softened, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Use a #spoon{} to break it up as it cooks, then drain and discard any excess fat. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince. The pork is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Add the remaining garlic, @Cajun spice mix{1} and @tomato puree{30%g} to the pork. Stir-fry for ~{30%seconds}.

Next, add the remaining chicken stock paste, @sun-dried tomato paste{25%g} and @water{100%ml} for the sauce to the pork. Stir to combine, bring to the boil, then reduce the heat slightly and simmer until the sauce has thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Meanwhile, pick the @mint{1} leaves from their stalks and roughly chop (discard the stalks).

Stir half of the mint through the cooked bulgur.

Taste the pork and season with salt and pepper if needed.

Share the minty bulgur between your #bowls{}.

Top with the Cajun pork.

Finish with a scattering of the remaining mint.

Enjoy!